A Time-of-Flight (ToF) sensor works on a beautifully simple yet powerful principle — it measures distance by timing how long it takes for light to make a round trip between the sensor and a target object. 
The sensor contains two core components:
An Emitter and a receiver.
The emitter, typically an infrared (IR) laser or LED, fires a pulse or a continuous modulated beam of light toward the target.
The moment that light leaves the emitter, an internal high-precision clock starts ticking. When the light hits the object in front of it, 
it bounces back and is captured by the receiver, which is usually a photodetector or an array of Single Photon Avalanche Diodes (SPADs).
The clock stops the instant the reflected light is detected, and the sensor uses the elapsed time along with the known speed of light 
(approximately 299,792,458 meters per second) 
to calculate the exact distance using the formula:
Distance = (Speed of Light × Time) / 2 — divided by two because the light travels to the object and back.
There are two main techniques ToF sensors use internally.
The first is Pulsed ToF, where a short burst of light is emitted and the time delay of the returning pulse is measured directly —
this method is highly accurate and commonly used in LiDAR systems for autonomous vehicles and drones.
The second is Continuous Wave (CW) Phase-Shift ToF, where instead of a single pulse, a continuously modulated light wave is sent out,
and the sensor measures the phase difference between the emitted and received signals to determine distance 
— this approach is widely used in compact sensors like the VL53L0X found in smartphones and robotics.
The phase shift method is preferred in consumer electronics because it is power-efficient, fast, and works well at shorter ranges.
What makes ToF sensors stand out from other distance-measuring technologies is their immunity to ambient light interference (thanks to precise filtering), 
their ability to measure distance independently of the target's color or texture (unlike infrared reflectance sensors), 
and their extremely fast response time — often updating readings hundreds of times per second.
Modern ToF sensors also incorporate on-chip signal processing that handles noise filtering, temperature compensation, and cross-talk correction automatically, 
delivering clean and reliable distance data over a simple I2C or SPI interface to your microcontroller. 
This combination of accuracy, speed, and simplicity is exactly why ToF sensors are widely used in applications like smartphone face unlock systems, 
robotic obstacle avoidance, industrial automation, gesture detection, and liquid level measurement.
